# GoThru 3D API — Go Backend Implementation Plan (v3)

> **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development (recommended) or superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task. Steps use checkbox (`- [ ]`) syntax for tracking.

**Goal:** Build `gothru-3d-api/` — a standalone Go HTTP service providing auth, project CRUD, and file storage, called exclusively server-to-server by Next.js Server Actions (never directly by the browser).

**Architecture:** Separate Go binary (`gothru-3d-api/`) with its own `go.mod`. Uses **GORM v2** with the standard postgres driver (lib/pq) and a pool connection for all DB access. Issues plain HS256 JWTs (no prefix) returned in JSON — NextAuth on the frontend stores these as `accessToken`. All protected routes read `Authorization: Bearer <token>`. Email is sent via **Plunk track events** (template IDs configured as env vars). No cookies are set by the Go service — NextAuth manages the session. All routes live under `/v1/` (no `api` prefix). 500 errors return the real error message via `apierror.Sanitize` — never raw SQL. **CORS** is handled by `github.com/rs/cors` mounted as the first chi middleware; the allowed origin is read from `CORS_ALLOWED_ORIGIN` (defaults to `http://localhost:3000`).

**Tech Stack:** Go 1.26 · chi v5 · GORM v2 + gorm.io/driver/postgres · golang-jwt/jwt v5 · golang.org/x/crypto · github.com/google/uuid · github.com/lib/pq · github.com/rs/cors v1.11 · github.com/stripe/stripe-go/v76

## Global Constraints

- Go version: **1.26**
- All routes under `/v1/` — e.g. `POST /v1/auth/login`, `GET /v1/projects`
- No JWT prefix — `IssueToken` returns a plain HS256 JWT; `ValidateToken` parses it directly
- No cookies — login/register return `"token"` in JSON body; NextAuth stores it as `accessToken`
- `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header is the only auth mechanism for protected routes
- GORM v2 with `SetMaxOpenConns(25)`, `SetMaxIdleConns(5)`, `SetConnMaxLifetime(5 * time.Minute)`
- GORM AutoMigrate runs on startup — no separate SQL migration files
- Email via Plunk track events: `POST https://api.useplunk.com/v1/track`, event names from env vars
- Error shape: `{"error": "message"}` — 500s use `apierror.Sanitize(err)` (no raw SQL)
- CORS middleware via `github.com/rs/cors` — mounted as the first chi middleware, before auth
- Allowed origin: `CORS_ALLOWED_ORIGIN` env var (default `http://localhost:3000`); allowed methods: GET, POST, PATCH, DELETE, OPTIONS; allowed headers: `Authorization`, `Content-Type`; `AllowCredentials: false`
- Env vars: `DATABASE_URL`, `GOTHRU_3D_JWT_SECRET`, `PLUNK_API_KEY`, `NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL`, `PLUNK_VERIFY_EVENT`, `PLUNK_RESET_EVENT`, `DATA_DIR` (default `/data`), `PORT` (default `8080`), `CORS_ALLOWED_ORIGIN` (default `http://localhost:3000`), `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY`, `STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET`, `STRIPE_PRICE_ID`
- Tests: Go stdlib `testing` + `net/http/httptest`
- No source file may exceed 500 lines — if a file grows beyond this during implementation, split it into focused sub-files before committing (e.g. `internal/auth/handler_register.go` + `internal/auth/handler_login.go` + `internal/auth/handler_password.go`); each sub-file must still compile independently

